As shown in the Fig. S2, the membranes were prepared without non-woven substrate. It is obvious that our membranes has no damage after being folded in half, which means they are robust and flexible for both pristine TFC membrane and CQDs/TFC membranes with different loading concentration of CQDs. Fig. S3 presents morphology of PES substrates before and after CQDs coated. There is no significant change of morphology which may be because the small-size CQDs (6 nm) are hardly to be observed. Fig. 1
                         shows the effects of CQDs on the surface morphology of CQDs/TFC membranes which were prepared by PEI with molecular weight of 70 K. The TFC membrane without CQDs shows a relatively flat surface, which is typical for TFC membranes fabricated with large-molecular PEI as monomer. With the increase of CQDs loading, small particles appear on the membrane surface. The morphological evolution could be caused by the change in crystallinity of the interfacial polymerized layer, which can be evidenced from the XRD (Fig. 2
                        ) of the CQDs/TFC membrane. The higher peak intensity corresponds to the increase in the crystallinity of the membrane surface, which is the result of more regular arrangement of polymer chains from interfacial polymerization. The carboxyl groups of the CQDs will react with PEI which will be explained in the next section. Thus the migration of PEI during the interfacial polymerization will be limited. As the amount of CQDs increases, the crystallinity of the interfacial polymerized layer gradually enhances. A portion of the interfacial polymeric chains will crystallize and become small particles that appears on the surface of the membrane [36,37]. In addition, the surface roughness is basically maintained at the same level, where membrane with 6% CQDs (Fig. S4(d)) own the largest value which is the result of appearance of small crystal particles. Besides, the thickness of selective layer of different membranes (Fig. 1(e), (d)) is almost the same around 100 nm, which means that CQDs would not influence the thickness of the IP layer.

The high retention of lysine by the CQDs/TFC membrane demonstrates the potential application of the membrane in biogas slurry valorization. The rejection of other model amino acids and the effect of pH were subsequently investigated. It can be seen that all amino acids show better retention under acid or base condition compared with neutral condition (Fig. 9
                        ). The reason is that amino acids are positively or negatively charged respectively in acidic or alkaline environment (Fig. S5). The trend almost agrees with the zeta potential curve of the CQDs/TFC membrane (Fig. 10
                        ). Besides, the stokes radius of amino acids (Table S1) are larger than the pore size of CQDs/TFC membrane. Thus, both pore size exclusion and Donnan effect are responsible for the high rejection of amino acids by the CQDs/TFC membrane. It is worthy to note that in contrast to the other two amino acids, the rejection of glutamic acid is lower under acidic and neutral conditions. This is because that the glutamic acid is neutral at pH = 3 according to the dissociation curve (Fig. S5(c)), and only size exclusion plays the main role for its rejection [42].
